[[File:Cosmic ray flux versus particle energy.svg|360px|thumb|Cosmic ray flux versus particle energy]]
'''Cosmic rays''' are immensely [[ionizing radiation|high-energy radiation]], mainly originating outside the [[Solar System]].<ref>{{cite book
 | last=Sharma
 | title=Atomic And Nuclear Physics
 | year=2008
 | publisher=Pearson Education India
 | isbn=978-81-317-1924-4
 | page=478
}}</ref> They may produce [[air shower (physics)|showers of secondary particles]] that penetrate and impact the [[Earth's atmosphere]] and sometimes even reach the [[Earth's surface|surface]]. Composed primarily of high-energy [[protons]] and [[atomic nuclei]], they are of mysterious origin. Data from the ''[[Fermi Gamma-ray Space Telescope|Fermi]]'' space telescope (2013)<ref name=ackermann-2013>{{cite journal
 | volume=339
 | pages=807<U+2013>811
 | title=Detection of the Characteristic Pion-Decay Signature in Supernova Remnants
 | date=2013-02-15
 | doi=10.1126/science.1231160
 | url=http://www.sciencemag.org/content/339/6121/807.full
 | publisher=American Association for the Advancement of Science
 | accessdate=2013-02-14
 | issue=6424
 | last1=Ackermann
 | first1=M.
 | last2=Ajello
 | first2=M.
 | last3=Allafort
